  "prompt": "In Bhagavad Gita 18th chapter, Lord Krishna says \"Arjuna is his dearest friend\". I am curious to know if there are any stories in Arjuna's previous birth, to become Lord's dearest friend in Vishnu's incarnation as Krishna?",
  "response": "While the Bhagavad Gita itself doesn't explicitly detail Arjuna's past life and how it directly contributed to their close bond, Hindu scriptures offer insights that suggest Arjuna's previous births played a significant role in forging that intimate connection with Krishna. Here's a breakdown of those potential connections:\n\n*   **Nara-Narayana:** The most prominent explanation lies in the concept of Nara and Narayana. Ancient scriptures, including the Mahabharata itself, identify Arjuna as the incarnation of Nara, a sage who was eternally paired with Narayana. Narayana, in this context, is considered an earlier avatara (incarnation) or aspect of Vishnu. Krishna is considered a later and more complete incarnation of Vishnu/Narayana. Nara and Narayana performed intense austerities together for the welfare of the world. This eternal companionship and shared devotion in previous ages naturally leads to a strong, pre-existing bond in their Krishna-Arjuna incarnations. This is referenced in the Mahabharata, indicating their connection is ancient and predates this particular birth.\n\n*   **Rebirths of Indra's son:** Arjuna is born to Kunti Devi, with the blessing of Indra. Indra is the king of Gods and is a great devotee of Vishnu. Since, Arjuna is related to Indra, through birth, Arjuna become Vishnu's dearest friend.\n\nIn essence, the idea is that Arjuna wasn't just a random individual who happened to become Krishna's friend. Their relationship was preordained, rooted in their shared divine essence and past actions as Nara and Narayana. This inherent connection made Arjuna uniquely receptive to Krishna's teachings and guidance, solidifying their bond as the dearest of friends.\n",
